## Why 400 (not 5xx)
The client retry predicate weave/utils/retry.py:_is_retryable_exception skips 4xx (except 429) but retries 5xx. TOO_SLOW is deterministic for a given query+dataset, so retrying is pure waste -> 4xx stops it with zero client retry-code change AND drops it off the @http.status_code:50* SRE monitors (correctly labeling it user-error, the WB-33068 goal). 400 over 422 because 422 is reserved here for "unsupported field/value"; this is a valid query that's too broad. Memory/timeout siblings stay 502/504 (can be transient); deliberately diverging.

## Hints & warnings
- Registry matches by EXACT type (errors.py handle_exception: type(exc)), default formatter _format_error_to_json_with_extra adds error_code iff the exc has the attr -- so the explicit register() call is required and the body carries error_code automatically.
- handle_clickhouse_query_error branches are substring checks on str(e); ordering is fine because the TOO_SLOW message contains neither MEMORY_LIMIT_EXCEEDED nor TIMEOUT_EXCEEDED.

## Codebase discoveries
- The guard is intentional: WF_CLICKHOUSE_MAX_ESTIMATED_EXECUTION_TIME (environment.py, "estimated-time (TOO_SLOW) projection guard"), added #6709, decoupled from the runtime cap in #7336. Default DEFAULT_MAX_EXECUTION_TIME=60s; T-Mobile overrides to 36000s, so the guard fires only after ~16-20min of scanning.
- error_code precedent: CallsCompleteModeRequired (ErrorCode.CALLS_COMPLETE_MODE_REQUIRED) -> client http_utils.handle_response_error recognizes it. PR2 mirrors this for QUERY_TOO_EXPENSIVE.

